      <div>
        <head>Text Representation</head>
        <figure>
          <graphic url="../images/tr-mission.png"/>
        </figure>
        <p>Chaired by a corpus linguist (Stig Johansson), the members of this commitee were all what
          we would now call <soCalled>digital humanists</soCalled></p>
        <p>Their mission : to identify and find names for the <soCalled>significant
            particularities</soCalled> of written texts of all periods.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <head>Significant particularities</head>
        <list>
          <item>text organization, structure, and reference systems (paragraphs, lists...)</item>
          <item>significant variation in format </item>
          <item>punctuation and character usage </item>
          <item>annotation and hypertextual links</item>
          <item>editorial variation (correction, additions, deletion, critical apparatus ...)</item>
          <item> ... </item>
        </list>
        <p rend="box">What is text <hi>really</hi>? </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <head>Analysis and Interpretation</head>
        <figure>
          <graphic url="../images/ai-mission.png"/>
        </figure>

        <p>Chaired by a theoretical linguist (Terry Langendoen), the members of this commitee were
          all what we now call <soCalled>computational linguists</soCalled></p>
        <p>Their mission : to identify and represent every kind of linguistic <emph>and</emph>
          literary analysis</p>

      </div>

      <div>
        <head>The range of linguistic analysis</head>
        <p>See http://www.tei-c.org.uk/Vault/AI/air03.txt... <list>
            <item>Underspecification, uncertainty, multiple hierarchies...</item>
            <item>Phonology and prosody</item>
            <item>Morphology and word-level tagging</item>
            <item>Higher level syntactic analysis</item>
            <item>Structural ambiguity</item>
            <item>Anaphora and Deixis</item>
            <item>Idioms</item>
            <item>Figures of speech (not for this cycle)</item>
            <item>etc. etc.</item>
          </list>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <head>The EAGLES imperative</head>
        <p>A strong desire for standardisation of linguistic resources as part of the pressure
          to improve <soCalled>language engineering</soCalled> systems <list>
            <item> The EUROTRA affair</item>
            <item> An unusual convergence of government-funded commercial and research interests </item>
            <item> development of the socalled language industries </item>
          </list>
        </p>
        <p>Sadly, a complete description of linguistic concepts remains elusive </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <head>Feature structures</head>
        <p>Rather than a single standard set of linguistic descriptors, the TEI proposed a kind of
          "meta-model" which could be used to represent any kind of linguistic annotation. Such
          representations could be used to make systems mutually comprehensible or even unifiable. </p>
        <p>A two level model : <list>
            <item>representation of the analysis as a bundle of  <term>typed feature structures
              </term> linearised in XML </item>
            <item>definition of a <term>feature system</term>, specifying constraints on the
              components and composition of such feature structures, aimed to support definition of
              a unification grammar. </item>
          </list>
        </p>


